SUMMARY:What Can We Do About It Here? Session 1
LOCATION:Brewbakers\, 48 Emerald St\, Keene\, NH\, 03431
DESCRIPTION:“What can we do about it here? A series of public discussions on political crises to build community solidarity”  Hosted by Cooperative Action Monadnock Session 1: “What can we do about a violent and unaccountable government?” Each session will include three community panelists discussing aspects of current political crises and then lead an open public discussion.  5-7pm. Free.\n\nSource: Nova Arts\n\nDetails: https://www.novaarts.org/events/whatcanwedo1
URL:https://www.novaarts.org/events/whatcanwedo1
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vt-event-136@things-we-love
DTSTAMP:20260216T232417Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T220000
SUMMARY:The Gaslight Tinkers
LOCATION:Stone Church\, 210 Main St\, Bellows Falls\, VT
DESCRIPTION:The Gaslight TinkersLuke ConcannonFriday February 20Minimum age:All agesShow time:8:00 PMDoors open:7:00 PMStone ChurchTicketsDescriptionThe Gaslight Tinkers' mix of global rhythms creates a joyous world beat sound around a core of traditional New England old time and Celtic fiddle music, merging boundless positive energy with melody and song. Drawing from their extensive musical backgrounds in traditional folk, Caribbean, old time, Celtic, and rock, I-Shea, Clara, Garrett, Elie, and Peter craft a sound that brings world traditions togetherLuke Concannon has early memories of falling asleep at irish family parties to the sound of guitars, singing, and dancing. he has been making music in community ever since. upon meeting double-bassist john parker in school, the two formed the folk hip-hop duo nizlopi (best known for the ‘jcb song’), selling a million records in their twenties and deeply influencing the young ed sheeran who interned with them. through the strain of recording and touring world-wide with a small family-run label, nizlopi parted ways.invigorated by a hitch-hiking trip to palestine, luke wrote his first solo album, ‘give it all,’ kindling the fire for a solo singer-songwriter career. ‘ecstatic bird in the burning,’ luke's 2022 album, debuted at number 12 in the folk charts on both sides of the atlantic, including a number 7 single, ‘doing nothing,’ and garnered rave reviews:“CONCANNON DAZZLES … FOLK MUSIC WITH A LITTLE EXTRA SOMETHING.” – DANCING ABOUT ARCHITECTUREA pandemic collaboration with multi-instrumentalist composer Darius Christian  (Macklemore/Leslie Odom Jr) led to the singles ‘What Would You Change,’ ‘Brother,’ and ‘Dance with You.’ These and more appear on Luke and Darius's new album, ‘Midnight Bloom’ (2025).Luke followed his love, Stephanie Hollenberg, to the United States in 2016. Stephanie is a singer, creator, and spiritual caregiver, and frequently performs alongside Luke. Luke, Stephanie and their wee babe reside on Abenaki land, in a yurt in the Vermont woods with wonderful neighbours and a parliament of bard owls.LineupThe Gaslight TinkersLuke Concannon\n\nSource: Stone Church\n\nDetails: https://stonechurchvt.com#/events/158650
URL:https://stonechurchvt.com#/events/158650
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vt-event-176@things-we-love
DTSTAMP:20260216T232417Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T193000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T213000
SUMMARY:Queralt Giralt Soler Trio
LOCATION:Next Stage Arts\, 15 Kimball Hill Rd\, Putney\, VT
DESCRIPTION:Queralt Giralt Soler TrioA lyrical fusion of cello, voice, jazz, and Catalan folkFriday, Feb 20Minimum age:All agesShow time:7:30 PMDoors open:6:45 PMNext Stage ArtsTicketsDescription$22 Advance / $25 Door / $10 LivestreamCellist, vocalist, and composer Queralt Giralt Soler brings her deeply expressive trio to the stage for an evening of genre-blurring original music and inspired reinterpretations. Blending classical training with Catalan folk traditions, jazz, and contemporary sounds, Giralt Soler weaves cello and voice into a singular, intimate musical language.Based between the U.S. and Catalunya, she has performed internationally and collaborated with renowned artists including Kenny Barron, Joe Lovano, and Latin Grammy winners Las Migas, with performances heard at venues such as Carnegie Hall and the Detroit Jazz Festival. Joined by Mahya Hamedi on piano, percussion, and vocals, and Bahar Badiei on oud and vocals, the trio will present Giralt Soler’s original compositions alongside reimagined works by influential composers such as Hermeto Pascoal and Paco de Lucía—music that is lyrical, adventurous, and deeply personal.Funded in part by the New England States Touring program of the New England Foundation for the Arts, made possible with funding from the National Endowment for the Arts and the six New England state arts agencies.LineupQueralt Giralt Soler\n\nSource: Next Stage Arts\n\nDetails: https://www.nextstagearts.org/events-calendar#/events/168554
URL:https://www.nextstagearts.org/events-calendar#/events/168554
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vt-event-204@things-we-love
DTSTAMP:20260216T232417Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260220T200000
SUMMARY:THE FLYING ACE w/ Pipe Organ Score by Jeff Rapsis!
LOCATION:Epsilon Spires\, 190 Main St\, Brattleboro\, VT
DESCRIPTION:Can discrimination exist in an America where everyone is Black? That's among the questions posted byTHE FLYING ACE(Dir. Richard E. Norman, 60 mins, 1926).A former railway detective turned decorated fighter pilot comes home from the Great War just in time to foil nefarious local ne’er-do-wells and save the girl. The only "Race Film" production byJacksonville’s Norman Studiosto survive in its entirety features an all-Black cast led by Laurence Criner and Kathryn Boyd and inspired a generation of real-life heroes and first Black pilots to fly with the U.S. Air Force, the Tuskegee Airmen.The Flying Acewas inspired byBessie Coleman, America’s first black female licensed pilot, with whom filmmaker Richard Norman had discussed making an aviation movie. Unfortunately, Coleman was killed in an April 1926 plane crash while practicing for an air show at Jacksonville’s Paxon Airfield, now the Paxon School for Advanced Studies. Norman based…Show More\n\nSource: Epsilon Spires\n\nDetails: https://www.epsilonspires.org/event-info/the-flying-ace-w-pipe-organ-score-by-jeff-rapsis
URL:https://www.epsilonspires.org/event-info/the-flying-ace-w-pipe-organ-score-by-jeff-rapsis
END:VEVENT
